      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;cloth-simulation&#34;&gt;cloth simulation&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;HN link: &lt;a href=&#34;https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=43801179&#34;&gt;Cloth | Hacker News&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;article link: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.cloudofoz.com/verlet-test/&#34;&gt;@cloudofoz - Verlet simulation test&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;another good post: &lt;a href=&#34;https://pikuma.com/blog/verlet-integration-2d-cloth-physics-simulation&#34;&gt;Pikuma: Verlet Integration and Cloth Physics Simulation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A cool website about cloth interaction, implemented based on Verlet Integration. Gonna make one myself.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Verlet Integration plays an important role in many game physics engines. It&amp;rsquo;s less expensive than, for example, &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kutta_methods&#34;&gt;Runge-Kutta methods&lt;/a&gt; (though also less accurate), but it&amp;rsquo;s also much more stable than&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_method&#34;&gt;Euler method&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Have a feeling that I&amp;rsquo;ve heard these names in college.…&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
